File: Credit cards. Pixabay JOHANNESBURG - Consumer spending bounced back sharply in December, keeping cash registers ringing. The spending rose to an annual rate of 3.1 percent from the same period a year ago. This is thanks to the easing of lockdown restrictions creating an enabling environment for consumers to shop around. READ: South Africans spending more money on snacks: report Economists had forecast a 2.6 percent increase, according to a Bloomberg survey. For 2021, sales increased by 2.4 percent. The numbers reflect a recovery in the trading environment for retailers after a dreadful year in 2020 when sales contracted 7.1 percent. All seven types of retailers showed positive growth rates over the period.